    "summary": "The Battle of Lepanto (October 7, 1571 AD) was the largest naval battle of the 16th century, in which the Holy League — a coalition of Spain, Venice, Genoa, and the Papacy under the command of Don John of Austria — decisively defeated the Ottoman fleet off the Gulf of Lepanto on the western coast of Greece, ending Ottoman naval supremacy in the western Mediterranean and dealing the greatest Ottoman defeat in a century. The battle pitted approximately 212 Holy League galleys against 251 Ottoman galleys; the Holy League's strategic advantage was the deployment of six large Venetian galleasses (hybrid rowing-sailing vessels armed with heavy broadside artillery) at the front of the Christian line, which devastated the Ottoman advance.\n\nThe battle lasted approximately four hours; the Ottoman fleet was destroyed: about 230 of 251 ships were sunk, captured, or disabled, and approximately 30,000 Ottoman sailors and soldiers died. Crucially, the victors freed approximately 15,000 Christian galley slaves from the captured Ottoman vessels. Among the wounded on the Christian side was Miguel de Cervantes, author of [[event:3307|Don Quixote]], who lost the use of his left hand and later described Lepanto as 'the greatest occasion that the centuries have seen.' The battle's strategic significance was more limited than its symbolic impact suggested: the Ottomans rapidly rebuilt their fleet, recovered Tunis from Spain in 1574, and retained naval dominance in the eastern Mediterranean. But Lepanto's psychological impact on Christian Europe was immense — proof that the seemingly invincible Ottomans could be defeated — and it became one of the most celebrated military victories in European Christian history.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Lepanto",
